ially thought, but it somehow retained the same node ID as before, which is unusual. Let me verify the actual restart sequence by checking when each pod came back online. So with emptyDir, each pod restart clears the data directory and generates a new node ID. But the logs show es-0 and es-2 still have the same cluster state from term 32, which shouldn't happen if they were restarted. Looking at the timing: es-2 restarted 2m17s ago and is ready, es-1 restarted 34s ago, and es-0 is still at 12m—so the rollout is progressing through the pods in order, but something's off with how the node IDs are persisting.\n\nI need to check if the StatefulSet actually has volumeClaimTemplates in addition to the emptyDir volumes I saw, since that would explain how the data survives pod restarts. PVCs are defined in the `volumeClaimTemplates` section, which means the data persists across pod restarts since the volumes are managed separately from the pod lifecycle.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":9848,"cache_read_input_tokens":64159,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":9848},"output_tokens":20,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"719200ff-7cd2-49d6-aba3-40f90c5cb2aa","uuid":"1b7ed0cc-5583-4a04-922b-e1113baba6cc","request_id":"req_011CcMskN17RopG2Ge7iCCd7"}
