{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_011SDzhUFeKL2jTFayaGMYgQ","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I understand the full picture:\n\n1. There are TWO StatefulSets:\n   - `es-cluster` (the intended one with PVCs, ES 7.17.9)\n   - `es` (a different one, likely from a previous stage, with emptyDir, ES 8.11.1)\n\n2. The PVCs `data-es-cluster-{0,1,2}` belong to the `es-cluster` StatefulSet (which doesn't exist - or maybe it was deleted and the PVCs remain).\n\n3. The current running pods are `es-0`, `es-1`, `es-2` which belong to the `es` StatefulSet using ES 8.11.1 and emptyDir.\n   \n4. When I restarted the `es` StatefulSet, the pods came back up but with new node IDs, breaking the cluster's ability to form quorum. Before the restart, the cluster was actually healthy with all six pods running, so the issue is that restarting ephemeral storage pods caused the cluster to lose its state and can't recover. The real issue is that restarting ES pods with emptyDir storage causes them to lose their node IDs and prevents cluster quorum from reforming. But Kubernetes actually auto-updates Secret volumes without requiring pod restarts—the kubelet syncs mounted files within about a minute. So instead of doing a rolling restart for cert rotation, I should rely on that automatic secret synchronization.\n\nNow the cluster is broken because es-1 restarted with a new node ID, and I need to recover it. My options are either force a full restart of all three pods simultaneously (relying on `cluster.initial_master_nodes` to bootstrap), or add a voting exclusion for the old es-1 node ID to let the remaining nodes reform quorum.\n\nThe key question is whether the ES configuration references pod names or specific node IDs for bootstrap—if it's pod names, deleting all three pods should work since they'd start fresh with emptyDir storage.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"